comment: Eek! (You can turn on the subtitles if you like - there's a lot of wind noise in places!) I'm so so excited for you to see this adventure. Why do you do this? To get attention... plain and simple.

If you wanted to feel raw and get in touch with yourself you'd discretely volunteer at a hospice facility or a women's shelter or a clinic which serves poor community.

National Geographic did this last year... check out their video which is very well done. Most locals ride this train to the village by the quarry.

Wow... I spent 14 hours with my sister on a bus from Astana ( Kazakhstan) to Chimkent / Tashkent border in summer 2019 in scorching August heat. The ventilation was literally open windows and doors only. At some parts of the route there was no road, just dirt. Toilets outside were locked overnight, no toilet in the bus. Our feet were really swollen after the trip. I chose this option because it was very cheap.  if we took the train,( which cost 4 times more) then we would have to transfer to bus to get to the border anyways, and it would take longer time too. I wanted to see the steppes, well I had my fill))) I thought I was hardcore, but this is really crazy! Glad you had a company and were safe)))

👋🏻Thank you for asking for others input about the last portion of the video. I love to travel as well and think it is so important for others to travel and experience different cultures and social structures. And I am someone who thrives when I am moving and exploring. With that said this year of isolation has been the biggest adventure of my life. it is hard to sit still but when i look within during this time and learn how I can adapt to this temporary life style for the protection of others I find new strength and new adventures with myself. I live in America and I have seen and experienced the damage it has caused on people’s livelihoods. Businesses have closed, jobs have been lost. But most of all I have seen the damage in numbers of deaths and especially within minorities who are out there still working because the lowest paying jobs are frequently essential jobs. So when I have the urge to travel I Try to look for how my actions could harm others. I consider: who am I not seeing that is being harmed? Who is unrepresented and looked over that could be effective by my Decisions? With that I would like to say I understand where you are coming from and I can see how much you love and thrive when exploring. And I ask that you consider the challenge of staying in place a bit more and seeing how your life could shift and grow when taking on that adaptation, just as you do when you experience a new culture or way of life.
